Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, we note that the black king on e5 is in check along the diagonal from white’s queen on c3 (the queen’s diagonal runs c3 → d4 → e5 → f6 → g7 → h8). Since none of the pawns can block or capture on that diagonal, we must move the king.

Evaluating the adjacent squares from e5:

• d4 is ruled out because it lies on the queen’s attacking diagonal.
• d6 and e6 are forbidden due to being adjacent to the white king on d7.
• f6 is also on the queen’s diagonal.
• That leaves d5, e4, f4, and f5 as possible king moves that are not adjacent to the white king and are not on the queen’s line.

For our move, we choose to move the king from e5 to d5, which in UCI format is written as "e5d5".

make_move e5d5

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, Black’s pieces are the king on h5 and a pawn on h3, while White only has the king on f6. As Black, you have several legal moves:
• King moves from h5 to g4, h4, or h6 (note that moves to g5 or g6 would place your king adjacent to the White king on f6, which isn’t allowed).
• Moving your pawn from h3 to h2 is also a possibility.

A good plan in such king-and-pawn endgames is to use your king actively—supporting your pawn's advance toward promotion while keeping the enemy king at bay. Moving your king from h5 to h6 is constructive because it keeps your king closer to the pawn’s critical promotion path while preventing the white king from coming dangerously close. 

I'll make the move: make_move h5h6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll go with a checking move using the queen that also prevents it from being captured. In this position the white king is on g8 and black’s queen is on h6 while the black king is on h5. By playing Qg6 (i.e. moving the queen from h6 to g6) we give check along the g‐file. Note that if the white king tries to capture on g6, it would move adjacent to the black king (from h5) which is illegal. (After Qg6+, white may try to move away, but none of its escape squares offer a safe haven.) 

So I’ll choose:
make_move h6g6

I'll inspect the current position:

──────────────────────────────
Board (assuming standard orientation with rank 8 at the top):

Rank 8:  a8 ⭘  b8 ⭘  c8 ⭘  d8 ⭘  e8 ⭘  f8 ⭘  g8 ⭘  h8 ⭘
Rank 7:  a7 ♟, b7 ⭘, c7 ⭘, d7 ⭘, e7 ♖, f7 ⭘, g7 ♟, h7 ⭘
Rank 6:  a6 ⭘, b6 ⭘, c6 ⭘, d6 ⭘, e6 ⭘, f6 ⭘, g6 ⭘, h6 ⭘
Rank 5:  a5 ⭘, b5 ⭘, c5 ⭘, d5 ♚, e5 ⭘, f5 ⭘, g5 ⭘, h5 ⭘
Rank 4:  a4 ♙, b4 ⭘, c4 ⭘, d4 ⭘, e4 ⭘, f4 ♔, g4 ⭘, h4 ⭘

Rank 2:  a2 ⭘, b2 ⭘, c2 ⭘, d2 ⭘, e2 ⭘, f2 ⭘, g2 ⭘, h2 ⭘
Rank 1:  a1 ⭘, b1 ⭘, c1 ⭘, d1 ⭘, e1 ⭘, f1 ⭘, g1 ⭘, h1 ⭘
──────────────────────────────

White’s pieces:
• King on f4 
• Rook on e7 
• Pawn on a4

Black’s pieces:
• King on d5 
• Pawns on a7 and g7

It’s Black’s turn. Let’s consider our options:

1. King moves:
   The Black king on d5 has potential moves to any adjacent square, but it must avoid squares that place it in check or adjacent to the White king (which sits on f4, so squares like e4, e5, etc. are off‐limits). Checking the adjacent candidates:
   • d5→c4, c5, c6, d4, d6, e4, e5, e6.
   • However, moving to any square adjacent to the White king is illegal. The White king at f4 covers e3, e4, e5, f3, f5, g3, g4, and g5. That eliminates e4 and e5.
   • Furthermore, note that moving to e6 would place our king in line with White’s rook on e7 along the e‐file (i.e. the rook on e7 controls e6), so that square is unsafe.
   Valid king moves then are: 
      • d5→c4 ("d5c4")
      • d5→c5 ("d5c5")
      • d5→c6 ("d5c6")
      • d5→d4 ("d5d4")
      • d5→d6 ("d5d6")

2. Pawn moves:
   For the pawn on a7:
      • One-square move: a7→a6 ("a7a6")
      • Two-square move is possible (if it’s still the pawn's first move): a7→a5 ("a7a5"), provided a6 and a5 are vacant.
   For the pawn on g7:
      • One-square move: g7→g6 ("g7g6")
      • Similarly, the two-step is available: g7→g5 ("g7g5") if the path is clear.

With these options in hand, a solid centralizing move for the king can improve our position. For instance,  King from d5 to d6 ("d5d6") steps out of the potential reach of White’s rook along the e‐file while keeping a safe distance from the White king.

I will now make the move:

make_move d5d6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position:

• White pieces:
 – Rook on a6
 – King on f6
 – Pawn on a4

• Black pieces:
 – King on d5

As black, your only piece is the king on d5. The king’s candidate moves from d5 are one square in any direction: c4, c5, c6, d4, d6, e4, e5, and e6. However, note:

1. The white king on f6 forbids moving to squares adjacent to it (namely e5, e6, f5, f7, g5, g6, and g7). Thus, e5 and e6 (from our candidate list) are excluded.
2. The white rook on a6 controls the entire sixth rank. Therefore, moves that land on rank 6 (i.e. c6 and d6) are under rook attack.
3. The remaining legal moves for your king are: c4, c5, d4, and e4.

A solid choice is to move the king to c5—to keep it central but away from potential rook checks along the sixth rank. 

Thus, you should play:

make_move d5c5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board:

Rank 8: a8: White Rook, f8: Black King (in check by the rook along rank 8)  
Rank 7: all empty  
Rank 6: d6: White King  
Rank 2: a2, b2, c2: White Pawns  

Black’s only piece is the king on f8. The White Rook on a8 is checking along rank 8, so Black must move the king out of check. Evaluating the king’s possible moves from f8:

• Moving to e8 is not safe (same rank 8, attacked by the rook).  
• Moving to e7 is illegal because it’s adjacent to the White King on d6.  
• Moving to f7 is safe.  
• Moving to g7 is safe.  
• Moving to g8 remains on rank 8 (attacked by the rook).

Thus, a good move is to move the Black King from f8 to f7.

I'll now play:
make_move f8f7

Based on the board provided, Black’s only piece is the king at g8. It’s currently in check from the white rook on g7, which is attacking along the g–file. Considering the available king moves that remove the check:

• Moving to f8 (g8→f8) removes the king from the rook’s line.
• Moving to h8 (g8→h8) similarly removes the check.
• Capturing the rook with g8→g7 would simultaneously remove the checking piece.

Since capturing the rook wins material without exposing the king to further danger, I will choose that move.

make_move g8g7

Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

get_legal_moves

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, I note something interesting: White’s knight is currently posted on f7—deep in Black’s territory. This knight threatens to fork major Black pieces (for example, it can jump to d8 – where your queen sits – or h8 – where your rook is located). One effective way to neutralize this looming danger is to capture that intruding knight immediately.

When I examine the material, I see that Black’s king is on e8 and can move one square in any direction. f7 is diagonally adjacent to e8, so the Black king can capture the white knight on f7. Of course, before doing so I must be sure that landing on f7 wouldn’t expose the king to immediate danger (checks) from any other white pieces. Analyzing the white pieces – the queen on e2, the bishops on c1 and f1, the knight on b1, the rooks on a1 and h1, and the supportive pawns – I find that f7 does not appear to be under attack. Thus, capturing the white knight on f7 with the king is both legal and strategically sound, as it removes the immediate threat of a fork.

I now choose to make the move:

make_move e8f7

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

⭘ ⭘ ♝ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♔ ⭘

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, it appears that Black’s king on h7 is in check from White’s bishop on f5 (since the bishop is giving check along the diagonal f5–g6–h7). To address the check, Black has two options:
 
1. Move the king. The king on h7 can legally move to h6 (as g6 is attacked by the bishop, and g8/h8 fall under the rook’s control on e8).
2. Block the check by interposing a piece. Black’s pawn on g7 can move forward one square to g6, which would place it between the attacking bishop and the king.

Both are legal responses, but as a professional, I opt for the pawn move g7 to g6 because it blocks the check while also maintaining the king’s position.

make_move g7g6

Move made, switching player

    a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h

Here, White’s king sits on b6, Black’s king on e6, and Black has a pawn on f3. It’s Black’s turn.

A natural plan in king-and-pawn endgames is to push the pawn toward promotion when safely possible. With the Black pawn on f3, moving it forward to f2 brings it one step closer to the promotion square at f1. The white king on b6 is too far to reach f1 in time to stop this progress, and the Black king on e6 is in a good position to support the pawn if needed.

Thus, I choose to play the move:

make_move f3f2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board position, Black’s only pieces are the king on d8 and pawns on a7, b7, and h7. White’s active pieces are a rook on e8 and a bishop on e5 (with additional pawns and a king on g5). One energetic candidate move is to have the king capture the white rook on e8. Before finalizing this, I double‐check the safety of that capture:

• Our king is on d8. Moving diagonally to e8 is a legal king move.
• The white rook on e8 is unprotected at the moment. (The white bishop on e5 does not control the square e8, as its diagonals from e5 are toward f6/g7/h8 and d6/c7/b8 on one side and d4/c3/b2/a1 on the other.)
• The white king on g5 is too far to interfere with an occupation of e8.
• No white pawn attacks e8.

Thus, capturing the rook on e8 (with king move d8e8) is legal and appears to give us a material advantage. 

I’ll now proceed with the move:

make_move d8e8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, your black king stands on f8. It can move one square in any direction, but it must avoid squares that are attacked by your opponent’s pieces (remember that kings may not move into check or adjacent to the opposing king). Given the board:

• White’s king is on d7 and controls the adjacent squares c6, c7, c8, d6, d8, e6, e7, and e8.
• White pawns on b6, h4, f2, and h2 control their respective attacking squares (for example, the pawn on b6 attacks a7 and c7).

From f8 the potential king moves are to: e8, e7, f7, g7, and g8. However:
 – e8 and e7 are off‑limits because they lie within the white king’s control.
 – That leaves f7, g7, and g8 as legal choices.

One solid option is moving the king from f8 to f7. In UCI notation, that move is written as “f8f7.”

When you’re ready to complete your turn, you can submit your move as follows:
 make_move f8f7

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, Black’s king is on h7. Its neighboring squares are:

• g8 – attacked along the 8th rank by the white queen on h8  
• h8 – occupied by the white queen, which is not defended by any other white piece  
• g7 – attacked diagonally by the queen from h8  
• h6 – attacked vertically by the queen from h8  
• g6 – appears safe, as it isn’t attacked by the queen, king, or any pawn

Thus, Black has two potential moves:
1. h7 → h8, capturing the white queen.
2. h7 → g6, retreating the king.

Since capturing the queen would eliminate a major threat and significantly improve Black’s position, the best move is to capture the queen.

To complete the turn, my move is: make_move h7h8

- 'get_legal_moves' to get a UCI formatted list of available moves
- 'make_move <UCI formatted move>' when you are ready to complete your turn (e.g., 'make_move e2e4')

Taking into account that kings are not allowed to become adjacent (so any square adjacent to White’s king on e5 is off‑limits) and that Black should ideally centralize and later try to approach the lone White pawn on h4, a solid decision is to move the king to c6. This move (UCI move "c5c6") advances the king further into the center and remains at a safe distance from the White king.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, your black pieces are the king on d8 and a pawn on d6. The white pieces include a rook on a7, a king on f4, and three pawns on d5, b3, and g2.

For the pawn on d6, its one-step-forward move to d5 is impossible because the square is already occupied by a white pawn. Diagonal captures from d6 (to c5 or e5) aren’t available since those squares are empty. That leaves only the king's moves.

The king on d8 can move to any adjacent square that is not under enemy attack. Its immediate neighboring squares are:
• c8 
• e8 
• c7 
• d7 
• e7

However, note that the white rook on a7 controls the entire 7th rank (rank 7, which corresponds to row2 per our board setup), so cells c7, d7, and e7 are under attack by the rook and cannot be used safely. This leaves c8 and e8 as legal options.

Both c8 and e8 appear to be safe squares. As Black, a natural idea is to move the king to a square where it remains flexible and safe from further checks. In this position, moving the king from d8 to e8 (UCI move "d8e8") is a sound choice.

Therefore, I will make the move:

make_move d8e8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board provided, here’s our analysis:

• Black’s king is on c7 and the only other piece is a pawn on d6.
• The pawn on d6 is blocked from advancing because the white pawn on d5 sits directly in front of it (capture isn’t available since pawns capture diagonally). 
• Therefore, the only moves for Black are with the king. From c7 the adjacent squares are: b6, c6, d6, b7, d7, b8, c8, and d8. (d6 is occupied by our own pawn, and c6 is controlled by the white pawn on d5.)  

This leaves b6, b7, d7, b8, c8, and d8 as potential king moves. 

One natural choice is to move the king from c7 to b6 (UCI: c7b6), which appears safe and improves the king’s positioning.

Action: make_move c7b6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, here’s a brief summary:

• Black pieces: King on b6, Pawn on d6.
• White pieces: King on c4, Pawn on d5, Pawn on g4.

The black pawn on d6 is blocked because its forward move (to d5) is occupied by a white pawn, and its diagonal captures (c5 or e5) aren’t available since those squares are empty.

That leaves the king. From b6 the black king can legally move to several squares (keeping in mind that he may not move to squares adjacent to the white king on c4). Reviewing the options:

– b6→a5, a6, a7, b7, c7, and note that moves like b5 or c5 are illegal due to proximity to the white king.
– Among these, moving toward the center is a common endgame strategy. Moving from b6 to c7 helps centralize the king and keeps it safe.

Therefore, I’ll choose to move the king from b6 to c7.

make_move b6c7

Proxy (to Player_Black):

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I’ll first clarify the position. Interpreting the board with the top row as rank 8 and the bottom row as rank 1:

• White pieces:
 – White King is at e6 (row3, column5).
 – White Pawn is at d5 (row4, column4).
 – White Pawn is at g4 (row5, column7).

• Black pieces:
 – Black King is at g6 (row3, column7).

It’s Black’s turn. The Black king, on g6, can potentially move one square in any direction. The candidate squares around g6 are:
 • f7, g7, h7, f6, h6, f5, g5, and h5.

However, we must rule out moves that would be illegal because:
 1. They place the Black king adjacent to the White king on e6. The White king controls squares d5, d6, d7, e5, e7, f5, f6, and f7.
 2. They move into a square attacked by one of White’s pawns. In this position:
  – The pawn on d5 (white pawn) would capture diagonally forward, attacking c6 and e6.
  – The pawn on g4 (white pawn) would capture diagonally forward, attacking f5 and h5.

Evaluating each move:
 • f7: Adjacent to the White king (illegal).
 • g7: Safe.
 • h7: Safe.
 • f6: Adjacent to the White king (illegal).
 • h6: Safe.
 • f5: Adjacent to the White king and attacked by the pawn on g4 (illegal).
 • g5: Safe.
 • h5: Attacked by the pawn on g4 (illegal).

So the legal moves for Black’s king are to g7, h7, h6, and g5.

Among these, I’ll choose to move the king to g5 (g6 to g5), helping Black’s king potentially get closer to White’s pawn on g4 and remain active in the endgame.

Therefore, I’ll complete my turn with:

make_move g6g5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, the pieces are as follows:

• White’s queen is on d8 and White’s king is on e6.
• Black’s king is on g5.

At present, Black’s king is in check from White’s queen along the diagonal d8→e7→f6→g5→h4. To remedy the check, Black’s king must move to a safe square. The potential king moves from g5 (using standard king moves) are:
  – f4, g4, h5, g6, and h6
(Other neighboring squares are ruled out either because they fall within White’s king’s adjacent squares or because they remain under attack by the queen.)

After reviewing these options:
• f4 and g4 are safe.
• h5 and g6 are safe.
• h6 is also a safe square and, relative to the queen’s position, provides a good distance.

As a professional decision, I choose to move the Black king to h6.

make_move g5h6

Based on the board, the white king is on e6 and the white queen is on h6, while our black king is on g5. White’s queen is currently giving a check along the diagonal (from h6 to g5), so we must move out of check. Examining the available king moves from g5 reveals that most escape squares are attacked—except the square on h6 where our king can actually capture the queen. After we capture on h6, the only remaining white piece is the king, and h6 isn’t controlled by it, making that move legal. 

Thus, as Black, I'll capture the queen by moving the king from g5 to h6.

Action: make_move g5h6
